title: Can't make GPT2 working with past state
body:
**Describe the bug**
GPT2-XL exported to ONNX with past state works when `past_sequence_length=0`. But when I start generating actual text autoregressively, it doesn't work:
```
RuntimeError: Error in execution: Non-zero status code returned while running Attention node. Name:'GptAttention_1' Status Message: Inputs 'mask_index' with raw attention mask shall have shape batch_size x (past_sequence_length + sequence_length)
```
Although `attention mask` has exactly the shape of  `batch_size x (past_sequence_length + sequence_length)`.

**Urgency**
My company's project is blocked because I can't get optimized GPT2 to production.

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): Debian 9
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): Binary
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.4.0
- Python version: 3.7.6
- CUDA/cuDNN version: 10.1
- GPU model and memory: Nvidia T4 16Gb + 51Gb RAM
- Pytorch version: 1.5.0+cu101

**To Reproduce**
1. cd to `onnxruntime/python/tools/transformers`
2. Export GPT2-XL to ONNX with past like this (you might also need a fix from [here](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/4707))
```

--model_name "gpt2-xl" \
--cache_dir "./cache_models" \
--onnx_dir="./gpt2_xl_onnx_past" \
--test_times 10 \
--precision fp16 \
--optimize_onnx \
--use_gpu \
--batch_sizes "1" \
--past_sequence_lengths 1000 \
--result_csv gpt2_results.csv
```
3. In the same directory create an inference notebook:
```

import time
import torch
import os
import onnxruntime
import pandas as pd
from gpt2_helper import Gpt2Helper 

tokenizer = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained('gpt2-xl')
device='cuda'

    def __init__(self, onnx_model_path,
                 model_class_name,

        self.device = device

        #shapes for IO binding
        self.empty_past_sequence_length=0

    def get_real_inputs(self,

        past_sequence_length = past[0].shape[3]

        position_ids.masked_fill_(position_ids < 0, 0)

        position_ids = position_ids[:, :]
        
        print('input_ids.shape', input_ids.shape)

        print('attention_mask.shape', attention_mask.shape)

    def __call__(self, input_ids, past=None):

        if past:
            past_sequence_length = past[0].shape[3]

            print('past_shape', past[0].shape)
        else:
```

Different kernel implementations sometimes very different results. This PR aims at providing flexibility to switch back to Pytorch code when debugging such issues. We basically

1. Add a flag to indicate the use of pytorch
2. Modify CMake files to build ORT with pytorch library
3. Add some helpers function to bridge ORT tensors and Pytorch tensors
4. Dispath MatMul to pytorch when USE_TORCH is set.

title: [WIP] Set `GraphResolveNeeded(true)` after adding a node
body:
**Description**: Adds a call to `GraphResolveNeeded(true)` in `Graph::AddNode()`, and calls `Graph::Resolve()` after modifying the graph in `MatMulScaleFusion`.

**Motivation and Context**
- At present, after calling `Graph::AddNode()` (e.g. in an optimization pass) the `Node::op_` field for the added nodes may be nullptr. This can cause segfaults in subsequent code that accesses this field.
- We must also actually resolve the graph during the optimization pass, to ensure that the nodes we access during the same pass are resolved.

title: Support RegisterCustomOpsLibrary via the Python API
body:
**Description**: `RegisterCustomOpsLibrary` is a mechanism via which custom kernels in shared libraries can be used to support a model containing ops not yet in the ONNX opset. This change supports it via the Python API.

There are some challenges associated with this:
1) Freeing `OrtCustomOpDomain`s associated with the custom kernels (https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/fdc5c308c4a579bcf96a170cffa3c00e761eb8cd/onnxruntime/test/testdata/custom_op_library/custom_op_library.cc#L120). Currently freeing is done by the user of C/C++ API via `OrtReleaseCustomOpDomain()`. In Python, just like in C/C++, we rely on the implementer of the shared library to release the OrtCustomOpDomains created within it (i.e.) we don't take ownership and manage the resource for the user.

2) Unloading the shared library
Currently the user has to manually unload the library via the provided handle while using the C/C++ API.  In Python, we unload the library automatically (no action needed by the user) when the last session using the session options connected with the shared library goes out of scope.

TODO:
- [x] Update relevant documentation in the custom op md files

- [x] See how this plays with the shallow copy and the deep copying mechanism offered by the `copy` module (https://docs.python.org/3/library/copy.html). If we think it is unsafe to allow deep copying SessionOptions instances in Python (because they hold associated OrtCustomOpDomain pointers), explicit disallow it by overriding the method for now until we have support for it. Python aliases are okay and they are not copies. For example, `so1 = Sessionoptions() so2 = so1`. This only creates aliases to the same object and preserves the object until all the referenced aliases go out of scope and this is supported. 
EDIT: It seems like currently `SessionOptions` isn't picklable. We need to investigate which instance attribute is causing the pickling issue and solve that. (Not sure if we even want to support pickling given that it could lead to security concerns). But given that it is not pickable, nobody will be able to shallow copy (`copy.copy()`) or deep copy (`copy.deepcopy()`) SessionOptions using the copy module and hence there is no action required. 

CC: @wenbingl

**Motivation and Context**
Fix https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/3958

title: Print Memory Requirements Before Real Allocation

labels.description: issues related to ONNX Runtime training; typically submitted using template

body:
**Description**: Display activation memory needed for Large Models

When we tried to understand the gaps on memory usage for large models (that cannot fit on one single GPU), we always need to know how much memory planned for initializers (e.g. training parameters) and activations (e.g. intermediate tensors). 

Initializers memory can be easily got from either the initializer planner (that happens before any CUDA memory allocation), or inferred from the parameter counts based on our knowledge on memory consumption.

For activations, we don't have such information.  This PR did this by just simply trying to generate a memory pattern earlier (for example before the initializer CUDA memory allocation) at the "best efforts", then we print it out, even though it will potentially fail later. The "best efforts" means, we try, but not necessary succeed. In the case where training graph have dim_param values, we will not have a successful memory pattern generated here, this is expected.

title: Enable metadata and signature changes in graph transformers
body:
After applying all the graph transformations the metadata and signature could have changes
(e.g.: new outputs got added, or the outputs/inputs got renamed). Therefore the local
copies of metadata and signature, that InferenceSession administrated for faster lookup, has to be updated, what isn't done so far. This leads to inconsistencies between the InferenceSession and the *actual* graph. And results in problems like (#4689).

As the metadata/signature orignially are stored  using `SaveModelMetadata`, this should be called after resolving the transformed graph in `Initialize` as well. Therefore I made the `SaveModelMetadata` execution idempotent by clearing the vectors/maps before refilling them. (There might maybe a better solution for this, especially for my concrete implementation). 


**Motivation and Context**
As described in issue #4689, i had a problem with not being able to set new outputs inside a graph transformer. While further investigating my issue, i thought about generally enabeling metadata/signature changes for graph transformers (mainly adding/removing/renaming in- or output)

title: Detect whether the node has been inserted cast nodes twice
body:
(*Updated)
**Description**:
`insert_cast_transformer` needs to be aware of whether the node has been cast before.
1. Add a additional Cast node check in `ForceSingleNodeCPUFloat16ToFloat32` to avoid inserting the same Cast Node twice.
2. Create the Cast Node name by `GenerateNodeName` to prevent future regression.
3. Add a unit test.

However, if the models have been done by inserting Cast node, some models will have some room to optimize the graph. (Because `insert_cast_transformer` is the last step in `InferenceSession`)

For example, the model given in the issue will output two different graphs if running `InferenceSession` with `onnxrt.GraphOptimizationLevel.ORT_ENABLE_BASIC` twice.

**Motivation and Context**
Fix the issue: https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/4745
onnxruntime InferenceSession (inserted Cast nodes) twice will cause a name conflict. (Same Cast node name)

title: Allow multiple sessions to share an allocator, optimize constant folding memory usage, expose arena configs.
body:
**Description**: Allow multiple sessions to share an allocator and optimize constant folding memory usage. 

**Motivation and Context**
* While debugging a scenario that involved 6 models per inference request, I observed that the cpu allocator (and hence the underlying bfc arena) was created for each session which led to suboptimal usage of the arena. This PR allows sessions to share the same allocator.
* Moreover, every node iteration in constant folding created a brand new instance of the CPU EP (and hence arena). This scenario had a large number of nodes where CF was getting applied. This PR reuses the same CPU EP that was registered with the session to execute CF. Not sure why we'd to create a new CPU EP. 
* In addition to the above, increasing the initial chunk size 10 times reduced the overall memory consumption of the application by 38%.
